**`InitializingBean`** is valid Spring API, but **`afterPropertiesSet()`** runs while the **`ApplicationContext`** is still starting — before the application is fully “up.”

**Problem 1 — Startup time.** Blocking **network** calls and **database** work on the startup thread add **startup latency**. In **Kubernetes**, slow boot can exceed **liveness** checks → pods restart in a loop even though the code “works” on a fast laptop.

**Problem 2 — Wrong place for remote work.** Remote systems can time out or fail. Doing that inside **bean init** mixes “create objects” with “talk to the world” without clear retries or feature flags.

**Problem 3 — Weaker fail-fast story.** You still fail if init throws, but the JVM may sit in a long half-started state while waiting on slow partners.

**Better approach:** Keep **`afterPropertiesSet()`** for cheap checks only (or avoid **`InitializingBean`** in app code and use **`@PostConstruct`** for light validation). Put heavy warm-up in **`ApplicationRunner`** / **`CommandLineRunner`** after the context is ready, optionally on a **background** thread, with **timeouts** and metrics.

```java
@Component
public class PricingWarmup implements ApplicationRunner {
  private final PricingClient client;
  public void run(ApplicationArguments args) {
    CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> client.refreshCache());
  }
}
```

**How to verify:** Enable **`management.endpoint.startup.enabled=true`** and inspect **`/actuator/startup`** for slow steps; compare boot time before and after refactor.

**Bottom line:** **`afterPropertiesSet()`** is not “free” — it runs at the worst possible time for long I/O.
